Salman is 81 and has been King for 12 months. The two Previous Kings have lived to 84 and 90. Both the previous two kings had been known to be unwell for years before they died. So the chances of him dying in the next 3 weeks are low (if we assume a life expectancy to match his brother Fahd a rough estimate suggests a less then 3% likelihood of dying in the next 3 weeks). There are three ways there could be a new King in Saudi, but odds of each are low: 1. Salman dies. But he is in good shape physically. He is likely to live around 10 years, leaving about a 1% chance he could die in the next month or so, with MBN presumably replacing him. 2. Salman is overthrown. We again put this as a low chance with MBN being the presumed replacement. 3. Salman steps down. Another 1% chance but this time with MBS as the most likely named successor.

I don't believe there will be a new King of Saudi Arabia before June 1st, because the Saudi Arabian kingdom has never transitioned from one generation to another, and no one is certain of what the outcome will be.

Last week, John Kerry "was received" by the King before moving on to a working meeting. If the King has Alzheimer's Disease, as rumors suggest, this announcement may have importance. Death from Alzheimer's is usually preceded by a period where your condition deteriorates to the level where it wouldn't make sense to for you to be receiving anyone, even in a courtesy ceremonial event. The fact that Kerry "was received" suggests the end may not be imminent, making it a little more likely perhaps that this question will time out.

The current King may be demented but there are good reasons why various parties might want to prop him up in a corner and keep him around for a while. This is not a simple succession struggle between MBN (CIA favorite) and MBS (youth gone wild). This is a complex conflict among powerful family factions and the stakes are high. The continuing existence of the House of Saud could be on the line. Succession is only the proxy question. Reaching consensus on an effective strategic vision for Saudi Arabia is the real question. Rumors about a quick succession quicken the pulse. But it seems more likely that the difficult internal argument about the real question will run on for a while. Having the current King in place, allows this pushing and pulling to continue.

I've been very low on one end of the see-saw with this question for quite some time, originally going with a base actuarial analysis that the current king had a good chance of surviving until June and the strange arrangement of power sharing would be maintained. I know the rumor of an imminent transition (weeks) may be bogus disinformation. However, many aspects of the situation in Saudi Arabia have deteriorated with surprising rapidity. I fear the notorious black swan is now circling over the House of Saud. I wouldn't be a bit surprised to see the regime collapse entirely and decamp to the Cote d'Azur, although maybe not before this question times out.

Saudi Kings rule until death, the rate of abidication is extrememely low (only one in 1964 when the King was forced into exile). As such the likelihood of abidication is low (though not zero as the challenges faced by the Kindgom are mounting due to a continued low oil prices, increased tensions with Iran and a backlash against the consolidation of power in the hands of the King, Crown Prince and Deputy Crown Prince which could force a change. In addition, there are rumors that the King is making moves to abdicate in favour of his son. (Estimate for probability of abdication - 4%) Death of the King: the current King is 80 years old, has suffered a previous stroke and is reportedly in poor health (though this is strongly denied) so the risk of death is relatively high but hard to predict in the coming 6 months - set at 35% chance). Therefore chance of a new king is around 39%.

The Saudi king is 80 years old, and had already had a stroke. According to the actuarial tables, there's an annualized 6.1% chance of him dying in the next year. (This equates to less than 3% before Jun 1).

Given recent events it may be that a radical change in political judgment is the only key to survival of the regime. Iranian retaliation isn't likely to be limited to words alone. Deposing the present King will need to be viewed as a response to address concerns in the Middle East and the West about growing sectarian divisiiveness. The political executions, if not paranoid in conception, were at least Ill-timed, and will not bode well for Saudi respect globally or their economy. It will be interesting to see how the US political race affects the future relationship with the Saudi royal family.

Re-allocation to cover the "Someone else" category per dominich reference.  I challenged dominich to participate in a public brainstorming with us, so it is only fair that I do likewise. Here are just a few items I suggest are at least interesting to consider: 1) I believe we can safely assume that "financial assets" are those that, upon instruction, can be converted into cash in some reasonable time. Generally liquid assets, cash and near-cash equivalents. Let's just say everything but hard assets (physical property). 2) Reports have it that the Saudi fortune, the so-called sovereign fund, which is entwined with the Kingdom, has experienced financial asset redemptions of anywhere from 12.5 to 20% over the course of the past twelve months. That is, simplistically speaking, the Saudi royals are calling their brokers with instructions to sell shares and send them the money. These redemptions, presumably, are going to expenses. The Saudis are, apparently, spending money far more rapidly than they are bringing it in. 3) Simultaneously, we have the story that the Saudi "strategy" of flooding the market with cheap oil is oh-so "successful." Everything must be done to preserve "market share." Well, if you just stop to think about it, the basic idea of a market share strategy in a natural resource commodity market is rather ludicrous. Sure, there are the logistical relationships, and the financial pressure placed on competitors. etc. But a natural resource commodity market has certain characteristics. a) The commodities, unlike, say, a factory that is tooled to produce automobiles, do not go away when the owners go bankrupt. New owners come in, but the commodities, in this case oil, remain. b) In such a commodities market, buyers take whatever is offered by whomever it is offered. The fact that you sold me oil last month at the best price (for which I paid and thanked you) should have little impact on whom I buy oil from this month. A marketshare strategy in a natural resource commodities market is, frankly, baloney. Since (Units Sold [Market Share] x Price/Unit) = Income is the inescapable economic equation, we see that this strategy of maximizing/maintaining market share is only half the equation. The rational goal is to maximize income, not market share. Rather than suggesting the Saudis are irrational, I suggest that the story of maximizing marketshare be recognized as only a component in some larger scheme; and considered by itself as only a ruse, a cover story. But a cover story for what? At the surface, it would be a cover story for the Saudis' massive depletion of their financial assets. Lacking such a story, the world would have wondered where the Saudis were suddenly taking such a large percentage of their wealth. They are doing something with it, but what? What expenses have they converted their redemptions into? Yes, there are expenses of the Kingdom -- but what goes elsewhere in the wash? What activities would require such massively large secretive funding? 4) Just for speculative consideration, couched in pure hyperbole for emphasis: What is it that the Saudis want so desperately that they are willing to spend hundreds of billions in bribery to obtain? And, who would be in a position to provide it for them?

wikipedia https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_of_Saud Succession has been from brother-to-brother since the death of the Founder of modern Saudi Arabia. Ibn Saud was succeeded by his son Saud. Saud was succeeded by his brother Faisal. Faisal was succeeded by his brother Khalid who, in turn, was succeeded by his brother Fahd. Fahd, as before, was succeeded by his brother Abdullah and Abdullah succeeded by his brother Salman, the current King. Salman appointed his half-brother Muqrin as Crown Prince in January 2015 and removed him in April 2015 because it would have caused Dynastic Instability, meaning that the Monarchy could have ended up because Princes who were becoming Kings were in their old age. Even Abdulaziz's youngest son was to turn 70 in 2015. Abdulaziz, in 1920, had said that the further succession would be from brother-to-brother not from father-to-son. King Salman ended the brother-to-brother succession and appointed his 56-year-old nephew Muhammad bin Nayef as Crown Prince in April 2015. He appointed his young son Mohammad, who is believed to be 30 years old (in 2015), as Deputy Crown Prince, thus making the next succession from cousin-to-brother, as Mohammad is the cousin of Crown Prince Muhammad.
